Thirteen climatologists and meteorologists at The Weather Channel's Drought  Symposium say added attention to climate has come from greenhouse effect worries and  media centers falling in drought areas, but climate concern shouldn't end with the  drought.
Questions over whether global warming is short- or long-term and its impact  means policymakers should deal with possible consequences and undertake sensible  policies: reduce fossil fuel reliance, become more energy efficient, replant forests, and  investigate alternative energy.
Countries' characters could change as higher temperatures  dry out the Midwest or melt polar ice caps.
Climatologist Gayther Plummer suggests  Jupiter passing the sun at its fastest point is related to SE drought in April and October. 
